The real Long March
Every nation has its founding myth.
For communist China, it is the Long March – a story comparable to the Israelites' exodus from Egypt led by Moses.
I grew up with that.
The myth is quickly told.
The young Communist Party and their three Red Armies were driven out of their southern strongholds by Chiang Kai-shek's nationalist government at the beginning of the 1930s.
Pursued and tormented by their enemies, they crossed high mountains, raging rivers, and treacherous grasslands, with Mao leading the march from victory to victory.
After two years and 16,000 kilometers of perseverance, courage, and hope against incredibly bleak prospects, the Red Armies reached Northwest China.
Only a fifth of the 200,000 soldiers remained – exhausted, badly wounded, but full of defiance.
A decade later, they struck back, defeated Chiang Kai-shek, and founded Mao's New China.
In what extent does China's founding myth stand up to reality?
In 2004, seventy years after the start of the Long March, I set out to search for its traces.
It is still a frightening journey through areas that have changed little to this day, inaccessible and incredibly poor.
Of the 40,000 survivors, perhaps only 500 are still alive today. I managed to find 40 of them and had conversations with them – they were normal people who were left behind or made it to the end, but their stories were extremely revealing.
Huan Zhiji was still a child, barely taller than his rifle, when he joined the Red Army.
He had no choice: They had arrested his father and wouldn't let him go until Huang agreed.
He thought about deserting, but stayed out of fear of being caught and shot.
Many fled.
Six weeks after the start of the march, Mao's First Army had shrunk from 86,000 to 30,000 soldiers.
The blame for this loss is still attributed to the Battle of the Xiang River, the army's first major battle during the march.
However, at most 15,000 died in the battle, while the rest disappeared.
Another battle, the Battle of the Dadu River, is at the center of the legend of the Long March. It is said that 22 brave men overwhelmed a regiment of nationalist troops that guarded the chains of the Luding Bridge with machine guns, clearing the way for the marchers.
Mao told Edgar Snow, the author of Red Star Over China, that the crossing of the Dadu was the most significant event of the Long March, and it is still celebrated as such today.
However, documents that I have reviewed suggest that the general who led the division across the Dadu told party historians a completely different story first. "The thing was not as complicated as people made it out to be later," he said. "When you examine historical facts, you should pay attention to the truth."
"How it is presented is a different matter."
The legend lives on.
There was only a skirmish over the Dadu.
The local warlord, who hated Chiang Kai-shek, let Mao pass.
As a reward, he later received a ministerial position in the communist government.
The march participants did not know where they were heading.
There were constant discussions about the final destination.
When they arrived in North China in October 1936, this was celebrated as the end of the March.
But the "promised land" was not as promised.
It could hardly feed its own population, let alone the Red Army.
The soldiers had no clothing to protect themselves from the freezing cold.
The women were ordered to turn back and return home because there wasn't enough food.
About a month after the three Red Armies united, the party decided that the Long March had to continue.
However, they were saved by the kidnapping of Chiang Kai-shek by the general whom Chiang had appointed to destroy the Communists.
As part of the price for his release, Chiang recognized the Communists as legitimate.
The Long March was over.
However, not for the 21,000 men and women of the West Legion.
They belonged to the Fourth Army, led by Zhang Guotao, Mao's arch-rival, and were tasked with seeking help from Russia across the western Chinese border.
But Mao gave them conflicting orders, so they could neither fight nor retreat.
Trapped in barren land where survival was difficult, they were annihilated by the superior forces of the Muslim warlords.
Only 400 reached the border, while the rest were killed or captured.
It was the greatest defeat of the Red Army.
Yet it is missing from the official historical narrative.
A Muslim commander took the leading officer Wang Quanyan as his mistress.
This was enough to make her a traitor in the eyes of the Party and deny her the years she had devoted to the army.
She and the other survivors of the Fourth Army had to fight for half a century to be recognized as participants in the March.
The participants of the Long March were steadfast, fought, starved, desperate, and persevered.
The hunger led the soldiers to take hostages in exchange for ransom.
The executions continued until practically no officers were left to take command in the battles.
When the marchers had doubts, they overcame them with communist propaganda.
They accepted their martyrdom with courage and self-sacrifice that is unparalleled in Chinese and other histories.

What drove them?
I questioned one of the highest generals about what he knew about communism back then. "I had no idea then, just like now," he replied. "I even doubt that Mao himself knew what it was." For him, who had survived extreme poverty and oppression, communism was a beautiful dream that kept him alive, the hope for a just and progressive society.
No one perhaps – or could – know how much suffering was still to come, how great the sacrifice, and how enormous the difference between the dream and reality would be.
